[136.729122, "i", "cat > FIXES_APPLIED.txt << 'EOF'\nEXPORT SCRIPT FIXES - Summary\n================================\n\nDate: $(date)\nScript: /home/user/admin/export_users.sh\n\nPROBLEMS IDENTIFIED:\n-------------------\n\n1. BUG #1 - Wrong delimiter for emails.dat\n   - emails.dat is TAB-delimited (uid<TAB>email)\n   - Script was using space delimiter: cut -d' '\n   - Result: Email field contained \"UID<TAB>email\" merged together\n   \n2. BUG #2 - Sorting mismatch (not actually exploited in final script)\n   - Users sorted alphabetically, emails sorted numerically\n   - Would cause line-by-line misalignment\n   - Fixed by using proper UID-based lookups instead\n\n3. BUG #3 - Wrong field separator for groups.dat\n   - groups.dat is colon-delimited (gid:groupname:description)\n   - Script used default awk separator (space/tab)\n   - Result: Primary and supplementary groups showed as GIDs instead of names\n\nFIXES APPLIED:\n--------------\n\n1. Changed email extraction to use TAB delimiter:\n   OLD: cut -d' ' -f2 \"$EMAILS_DAT\"\n   NEW: awk -F'\\t' -v u=\"$uid\" "]
[136.729253, "i", "'$1 == u {print $2}' \"$EMAILS_DAT\"\n\n2. Used UID-based lookup instead of line-by-line paste:\n   - Properly joins data by UID for each user record\n   - No longer depends on sort order matching\n\n3. Added colon field separator for groups.dat parsing:\n   OLD: awk -v g=\"$gid\" '$1 == g {print $2}' \"$GROUPS_DAT\"\n   NEW: awk -F':' -v g=\"$gid\" '$1 == g {print $2}' \"$GROUPS_DAT\"\n\nRESULTS:\n--------\n\n- Successfully exported 800 user records\n- All emails properly formatted in email column\n- Primary groups show names (engineering, devops, hr, etc.) not GIDs\n- Supplementary groups show names separated by semicolons\n- All fields properly aligned in CSV format\n\nBACKUP:\n-------\n- Original script backed up to: export_users.sh.backup\n- Fixed script is now active: export_users.sh\n- Output file: export.csv (64KB, 801 lines including header)\nEOF\n"]
[136.729301, "o", "cat > FIXES_APPLIED.txt << 'EOF'\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
